# ============================================================================
# SECURITY - Secrets Management
# ============================================================================
# API keys and secrets should NEVER be committed
.secrets
.secret
*.secret
secrets.yaml
secrets.yml
secrets.json
.aws/
.gcp/
.azure/

# ============================================================================
# COMMENTS FOR DOCUMENTATION
# ============================================================================
# This .gitignore file protects the repository by:
#
# 1. VIRTUAL ENVIRONMENTS: Excludes environment-specific files (venv, env, etc.)
# 2. CACHE & COMPILED: Prevents __pycache__ and .pyc files from bloating the repo
# 3. IDE FILES: Ignores editor configuration to maintain team independence
# 4. MODEL FILES: Excludes large binary models (use model versioning system)
# 5. DATA FILES: Excludes large CSV and raw datasets (use DVC or similar)
# 6. LOGS: Prevents log files from cluttering the repository
# 7. TEMPORARY FILES: Excludes swap files, backups, and OS-specific files
# 8. SECRETS: Prevents accidental commits of API keys and credentials
#
# RECOMMENDATIONS:
# - Use DVC (Data Version Control) for large files and datasets
# - Use GitHub Secrets for environment variables in CI/CD
# - Use .env.example for configuration templates
# - Consider using git-lfs for very large model files
# - Regularly audit commits with: git log --name-only | sort | uniq
#
# EXCEPTIONS (Files that SHOULD be committed):
# - .gitkeep files in empty directories
# - .env.example template file
# - requirements.txt (with pinned versions)
# - setup.py / pyproject.toml
# - README.md and documentation
# - Source code (.py files)
# - Configuration files (*.yaml, *.yml, *.json)
# - Test files
